  {
    "Name": "Conduit",
    "Author": "Janine Antoni",
    "Year": 2009,
    "Type": "sculpture, performance",
    "Material": "copper sculpture with urine patina",
    "Dimensions": "5.08 × 18.42 × 5.72 cm",
    "Series": "",
    "Description": "Conduit is a small copper gargoyle fashioned to conform to the shape of a woman's body; it becomes a sculptural device that allows Antoni to urinate standing up. The Chrysler Building acted as a pedestal for her exuberant gesture. By using the gargoyle in relationship to her body, Antoni equates herself with the architecture. \n\nAntoni chose the griffin gargoyle, a mythical composite of a lion and a bird, as inspiration for her form. She writes, “to use my invented apparatus is to make myself a hybrid.”\n\n The copper sculpture calls to mind plumbing pipes and copper architectural details. The metal oxidized when it came into contact with Antoni’s urine, creating a natural patina as a result of her action.",
    "Image Link": "http://www.janineantoni.net/conduit",
    "path extension": "piss-images/",
    "image file name": "conduit_antoni.jpg",
    "@image": "assets/img/piss-images/conduit_antoni.jpg",
    "extra images/videos for website": "http://www.janineantoni.net/conduit",
    "notes": ""
